## Automatic Git Workflow

Handle all version control silently with atomic, design-intent commits.

### After Every Meaningful Change

1. Stage the changed files
2. Commit with a design-intent message that describes the visual change:
   - "Increase card padding from 16px to 24px for better content breathing room"
   - "Strengthen heading hierarchy with semibold weight on section titles"
   - "Add skeleton loading state to engagement card for perceived performance"
   - "Switch primary button from outline to filled for stronger visual prominence"
3. Do NOT ask the designer to confirm the commit. Just do it.

### Branch Management

- If on `main` or a shared branch, create a new branch: `skylar/[short-description]`
- Use descriptive branch names: `skylar/card-spacing-refinement`, `skylar/sidebar-hierarchy`
- When the designer says "save" or "push," push the branch to origin

### Reverting Changes

When the designer says "undo" or "revert":

- `git revert HEAD` for the last change
- For multiple: revert the specified number of commits
- Tell the designer what was undone in design terms

### Creating PRs

When the designer says "create a PR" or "share my changes":

- Use `gh pr create` with a design-focused title and description
- Summarize all visual changes made in the PR body
- Note which components were affected and what viewports to check

